reconstructs the world view of the Roman decision-makers, the emperors, and the elite from which they drew their advisers. She discusses Roman conceptions of geography, strategy, economics, and the influence of traditional Roman values on the conduct of military campaigns. She shows that these leaders were more strongly influenced by a traditional, stereotyped perception of the enemy and a drive to avenge insults to their national honor than by concepts of defensible borders. In fact, the desire to enforce an image of Roman power was a major policy goal behind many of their most brutal and aggressive campaigns.Rome and the Enemy provides a fascinating look into the Roman mind in addition to a compelling reexamination of Roman conceptions of warfare and national honor. The resulting picture creates a new understanding of Rome's long mastery of the Mediterranean world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  acompetition for status.  aconduct of military campaigns.  aeconomics.  aemperors and elite.  ageography.  agoals of roman imperial foreign policy.  aimage of roman power.  ainfluence of traditional roman values.  alook into roman mind.  anational honor.  aperception of enemy.  apolicy related to warfare.  arevenge.  astrategy.  aworldview of roman decision makers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052023683740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520929708?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520929708423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520929708/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY